This sort-of exists, but isn't really exposed, and arguably should be. I don't have time to do a release this week (for various reasons), but in the mean time, you could add the following to any model you want the `.redis` attribute to exist on, and it would work exactly as you describe:

```
@property
def redis(self):
    from rom.util import _connect
    return _connect(type(self))
```

For the sake of having something that will work now and in the future (if you don't want to maintain this particular property on your models), I'm probably going to give it a name of `_connection`, and it will basically be the above property.

This works well for the first column filter, however it didn't for any other. I've instead removed the filter_cellFilter and adapted the CSS to match the following:
`@media ( max-width: 480px ) {
	.tablesorter-filter-row td:not(:nth-child(5)) {
		display: none;
	}
}`

See [here](https://jsfiddle.net/k8qjkL9p/5/) for the updated code.

In the end it was more of a CSS fix than a tablesorter one (unless we can specify the correct cellFilter in tablesorter somehow?). Thanks for assisting me though @Mottie.

Ah cool, thanks for the pointer to the example. In the meantime, I've bodged this workaround together:

```
class Point(collections.namedtuple('Point', 'x y')):
  name = ''
  def __str__(self):
    return '{} ({}, {})'.format(self.name, self.x, self.y)
```

It's good enough for what I wanted to do.

