@techalchemy - For sure, I concur that getting the tests back to green is a priority.  I'd be proposing to submit a PR once this has merged (in any case, a PR against a PR from a GitHub fork is too complex for me to handle!)

I suppose what I'm saying is that as complexity / entropy / duplication grows, the probability of divergence / bugs approaches 1.  That's just the reality I'm familiar with.  And CI is the last line of defence, so there's nothing further that could catch it in this case.

But given there's no direct way in Appveyor to clean this up, my proposed PR would be something like factoring out the duplicated lists of test markers (in both Travis and Appveyor config) to a single source of truth, and then also eliminating the duplication due to the `not` list.

I didn’t even know this was possible. People really can get creative with requirement specification. Flattening + merging hashes would cause a problem with the `version` key, I think? The only non-hack solution I can think of is to turn the dependency content into a list

```json
{
    "django": [
        {
            "hashes": [...],
            "markers": "python_version <= '2.7'",
            "version": "1.11.7"
        },
       {
            "hashes": [...],
            "markers": "python_version >= '3.4'",
            "version": "2.0.3"
        }
    ]
}
```

